abstract={In the era of the 4th industrial revolution, the worldwide blockchain market is forecasted to grow more than 10 times in the next five years and blockchain-based information sharing platform technology is expected to become an important infrastructure technology of high utilization value across all industries. However, clearly, blockchain has limitations that need to be solved and because it is still in the early development stage, the active advancement of the technology is developer-oriented; further,it is necessary to implement policies proactively to secure an early competitive edge at the national level. A blockchain facilitates trust-based information sharing through decentralization, but all information in a blockchain is open and permanently stored. Because of this, it is difficult to modify or erase data recorded in a blockchain; furthermore, the “right to be forgotten” cannot be guaranteed, which is important for maintaining privacy. If private information and sensitive information can only be stored permanently and cannot be erased, Blockchain cannot become a realistic business model in the information society where information protection is of the highest priority. In this paper, the technical and political limitations of the permanent storage characteristic of blockchain, which cannot be modified or deleted, are analyzed and the on-chain that stores metadata and the off-chain that stores full data are linked with hyperlinks. Moreover, technical and political approaches are proposed to implement the erasable blockchain technology of the hyperlink method, which facilitates modification and erasure of on-chain metadata, and the kill-button method, which changes a block’s data into an unusable state. © 2018, Institute of Advanced Scientific Research, Inc.. All rights reserved.},
